Well You Guys?<br>
     I just got home and found THIS!!!  I<br>
was ready to kick A..(nkles) and take <br>
names later, but you were all innocently <br>
asleep in your little beds.  I tried to <br>
step around it, but had to backtrack <br>
after reading Tom's letters (have to <br>
admit, his way with reason makes him one <br>
of my favorite &quot;sons&quot;).  Okay, at some <br>
point on this site each of you have had <br>
your say on this matter - my turn!!!<br>
(though I'm always the one to jump in to <br>
stop a fight, I'm also usually the first <br>
to start one - can't help it!!...It's <br>
hard being an Irish-Italian pacifist)!<br><br>
Barry,<br>
     I followed your posts for some time <br>
on POV and eventually I just had to stop.<br>
I sense that you sincerely are perplexed <br>
by the responses you have received and <br>
have effectively rationalized the reasons<br>
why.  For that reason, part of my heart <br>
goes out to you - I hate gang warfare and<br>
usually &quot;won't join any group that would <br>
have me as a member.&quot;  On the otherhand, <br>
I love what this site is offering to all <br>
of us (but especially for those who <br>
served in Vietnam) too much to not speak <br>
out against your attempt to trash it.<br>
    <br>
     Perhaps, just perhaps, you will be <br>
able to understand some of what has <br>
evolved from an outsider's perspective. I<br>
too, was a war protester.  I studied the <br>
Vietnam War in jr. high from a zealous <br>
social studies teacher who had convinced <br>
me in 7th grade (1965) of the &quot;commie <br>
threat&quot;.  I had him again in 9th grade <br>
(1967) and this time I had reached the <br>
maturity to do my own research.  After <br>
debating him on the subject (with only <br>
one other student in my corner) I came <br>
home to announce to my parents that I had<br>
determined that I was against that war. <br>
 My father a Navy officer, choked, but my<br>
mother gave me the floor to explain my <br>
reasons why.  I have always considered <br>
that as my &quot;coming of age.&quot;  Two years <br>
later my mother was active in the <br>
anti-war movement and my father was 100% <br>
behind both of us.  (I've summarized some of this on thread #122).  I'm giving you <br>
this history so that you understand that <br>
I wasn't a part-time follower - I came <br>
upon my &quot;liberal&quot; leanings honestly and <br>
with forethought.  I remember feeling so <br>
much hope for the future even amongst the pain and chaos of that time.  &quot;Our <br>
generation had the guts to truly change <br>
the world forever.  We were <br>
compassionate, educated, questioning<br>
blind obedience, and the hope of the <br>
future.&quot;, or so I thought.  By the time I went off to college, I became painfully <br>
aware of the nature of groups... Blind <br>
obedience? Compassion?...I watched fat <br>
college boys, sucking a beer, jeering <br>
vets on tv as they were getting off the <br>
plane to come &quot;home&quot;- it was insane - <br>
&quot;aren't these the guys we're trying to <br>
save?&quot; I asked.  I also <br>
listened to the inflated egos of several <br>
protest leaders revving up their <br>
unquestioning flock with nonsensical <br>
analogies and inaccurate information.  I <br>
don't remember anyone questioning...so <br>
much for the educated hope of the <br>
future...just more of the same wearing a <br>
different mask, enjoying the party. I <br>
have, since, abided by my innate <br>
skepticism of zealots and groups, in <br>
general, but never &quot;threw out the baby <br>
with the bath water&quot; and have remained an educated, idealistic independent thinker, still intent on pushing my country and <br>
countrymen to keep aspiring to be the <br>
best that we can be.  Many of my <br>
contemporaries are currently living in <br>
suburbia and their greatest cause today <br>
is their pocketbook. <br>
Some of them were sincere and are <br>
continuing to contribute to humanitarian <br>
causes.  And a few others, continue to <br>
espouse the same old tired rhetoric that <br>
independent thinkers are too old and wise to accept.  They were like any other group of people - a few zealots, a few true believers and lots of followers.  So your attempt to deify the protester is absurd.  Though many of your posts are <br>
coherent and often tease the reader with <br>
the promise of something fresh to digest,<br>
you never fail to go off on the stale old<br>
&quot;party line&quot; rantings that could only <br>
persuade the likes of mindless sheep.  You seem to fit the profile of the &quot;zealot&quot; drunk on the cause and the power of stealing the limelight for a few brief moments, but confusing passion for compassion.<br><br>
 You just don't seem to get it that the <br>
old &quot;flock&quot; has moved onto greener <br>
pastures.  But, more importantly, you're <br>
dangerous.  You're not inspiring <br>
constructive dialog.  You're perpetuating the bigotry and belief that all <br>
protesters were extremests and half mad <br>
zealots.  Your rantings threaten to <br>
completely close minds that were only <br>
half-closed before you were set loose. <br>
 The dichotomy between your declaration <br>
of war and your sermon of peace is <br>
unparalleled in the political world of <br>
&quot;doublespeak&quot;. Remember you are <br>
addressing Vietnam Veterans and there is <br>
something about their experiences that <br>
seems to have given them the ability to <br>
detect bulls__t sixty miles away.  I have learned to be very skeptical of others' <br>
ideas when their egos are their prime <br>
motivators.  Just take a look at the egos of Saddam Hussein, Stalin, Mussolini - no I am not saying you are like any of them <br>
- just that history has taught the wise <br>
to beware of men who are in love with <br>
their own voices, no matter how tempting their words may be.  You say the cause is peace, but your words are in search of war.  I think we are all wary of an errant, half cocked warrior with a nebulous agenda.<br><br>
But where I become totally incensed, <br>
Barry, is where you dare to compare your<br>
experiences to that of a combat veteran. <br>
My reaction was a loud &quot;HOW DARE YOU&quot;!!!<br>
For whatever reason they ended up in <br>
Vietnam (drafted or enlisted) many of <br>
these men experienced things that our <br>
wildest imaginations or nightmares could <br>
never come close to conjuring up.  It was at that point I realized that you could <br>
not possibly be a shrink.  Your <br>
insensitivity and blatant dismissal of <br>
the sacrifice these men made (regardless <br>
of your feelings about the war) is simply an outrage.  I have worked extensively <br>
with PTSD patients including victims of <br>
rape, physical abuse, and cult abuse and <br>
NOT ONE of those cases has been as <br>
pervasive as the nightmare that Vietnam <br>
Vets with PTSD have had to suffer through due to many complicating factors - I am in awe of the absolute determination and perseverance of many of these men.  If you had the vaguest understanding of what these men experienced, good and bad, in <br>
war and the postwar abandonment you'd <br>
understand why they band together, even <br>
when they disagree with one another.  But when you try your &quot;divide and conquer&quot; <br>
tactics, remember you're messing with <br>
&quot;family&quot;.  I (the one who refused <br>
to join any group) am honored to be the <br>
&quot;pack mom&quot; of this diverse family. And I <br>
don't want you to play with my boys <br>
anymore Barry until you learn some <br>
sensitivity and understanding and have <br>
that &quot;kick me&quot; sign surgically removed <br>
from your back, because, frankly, I'm getting tired of watching them kick the b'Jesus out of you.  Besides, they've got more important work to do here and you have been a rude distraction.<br>
 <br>
Now, speaking of extremists...Cook??? - Go to your room...I think your brothers need to talk to you in private.<br>
